:::summary
Frederick Douglass (c. 1818–1895) was the most important African American leader of the nineteenth century — a man who escaped slavery, taught himself to read, and became the most powerful orator and writer in the abolitionist cause, whose life was the most eloquent possible argument that slavery was incompatible with the founding ideals of the American republic.
:::

